I've been curious about 3800X's overclocking potential
Both it and the 3700X are 8c/16t processors, but the 3700X has a base/boost of 3.6/4.4 and the 3800x 3.9/4.5
TDPs are also 65W and 105W respectively
yeah you've lost me
TDP more or less represents how much heat they put out
ah, okay
I assume that the 3800X is able to OC higher because of the massively increased TDP, but at the same time... all outlets seem to be only able to get 4.3Ghz on all cores, regardless of processor
4.4Ghz if they're lucky and/or disable hyperthreading
Well, like I thought, nobody seems to have reviewed the 3800x
Seems like they weren't sent out to reviewers, so I wonder if you're paying an extra $70 for the increased base clock
Aka, worthless to manual overclockers
I thought all overclocking was manual
well, someone has to write a program for the chip to overclock, so in a way yes
but as long as there's an automation for it, then no.
I mean, they are inanimate objects after all, we have to do everything :P
It depends.  With Ryzen, there's 3 ways to go about it
You can leave everything stock, you can turn on PBO (additional OC on top of default settings), or manual OC
If you use either of the first 2, then the 3800X MAY be worth the extra $70, but the 25% increased price won't equate to 25% more performance (less than 10% increase to base clock, 2% to boost)
a default overclock someone had to write and code, so it's still manual technically. :P
just written so we don't have to directly do it every time
:robot:
Manual overclocking, on the other hand, in an uncontrolled experiment that only ends when either the hardware dies, or the experimenter is satisfied with the results >:3
well duh, but you know automatic overclocking would result in the same thing if it was also uncontrolled :P
you're talking about it like it's two coins when it's two sides of the same coin
Not exactly
The default needs to fit within a stricter range of tolerances that 99% of produced processors need to be able to meet
The manual oc, on the other hand, is up to whatever the overclocker decides is tolerable, and will push the chip however far that chip is capable of going.
yes actually. You're again deciding that two sides of a coin are not the same coin. ;u
I'm saying they're the same, but different -_-
from how it reads to me, tis the opposite. But I'll give ya a :knife: / 10
Here's a good question, how the hell could they be that different?
The entire point is to define the operational speed of the processor
Hey, you're the one stating they're so different. :V
It's just that one has to meet guidelines for things like temperature, voltage, and stability that will apply to (ideally) every processor that passes production
The other seeks to squeeze the most performance out of a given processor, and what the user defines as "acceptable" is unique to them and that processor
That doesn't scream "they are obviously two whole different beasts"
you and I have a very different definition of "different" :thinking:
Here's where I think the "two different coin" argument would come into play
Imagine if CPU manufacturers did manual overclocking for every processor they made xD
Mainly because of the absurdity of the idea

just because they don't doesn't mean it isn't possible. They don't due to probably already having pushed the chip to the point where it's being overclocked and them marketing as a "base" clock anyway.
When you think about it... the whole idea of "overclocking" is ridiculous
what we see as "overclock" and "base clock" are simply numbers. There's no baseline, it's all 100% arbitrary. Any core can have any baseline, and overclocking is just simply increasing it above.
We act like we're squeezing out extra performance (and we are), but it's because manufacturers leave performance on the table xd
The 9900k could easily have a baseline of 5ghz but the core would then be recieved as running very hot all the time and need superior cooling, etc
so they don't, they make it like 4ghz, so people can "overclock" it to 5 and see the same results just as if Intel had made 5ghz the base.
Well, maybe if intel's coolers weren't complete shite ;)
yes well, their coolers are irrelevant, it's all just theoretical anyway :v
this is just presuming they were a company with any shred of dignity in the past 10 years anyway lol
